<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1618,1791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1694,1719]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Behavior:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[328,423,1694,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[328,423,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Andrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are predominately solitary, although some species will form communal nests (
<bibRefCitation author="Osgood" firstAuthor="Osgood" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="56 - 64" refId="ref97719" refString="Osgood, E. A. (1989) Biology of Andrena crataegi Robertson (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae), a communally nesting bee. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 97, 56 - 64." type="journal article" year="1989">Osgood 1989</bibRefCitation>
). Species are often narrowly polylectic or mesolectic, but many species are oligolectic, specializing on a particular floral host taxon (
<bibRefCitation author="Linsley" box="[463,615,1766,1791]" firstAuthor="Linsley" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="543 - 599" refId="ref93468" refString="Linsley, E. G. (1958) The ecology of solitary bees. Hilgardia, 27, 543 - 599. https: // doi. org / 10.3733 / hilg. v 27 n 19 p 543" type="journal article" year="1958">Linsley 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Robertson" box="[627,809,1766,1791]" firstAuthor="Robertson" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="378 - 380" refId="ref100852" refString="Robertson, C. (1926) Revised list of oligolectic bees. Ecology, 7, 378 - 380. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 1929320" type="journal article" year="1926">Robertson 1926</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
